0iq39LHcgKZW2A6K9ZqQwK0YvuzqdwO_NKcZCXPbTJigWvFUXJpx1KPQ4suqwdX8yfVLStYmhtR=
cZCnBskdq9H8AV5OgFQ], and is now in the billions of dollars.=20
But that=E2=80=99s not enough; government must get in on this game, and sho=
vel money into the sector. One reason, of course, is climate change =E2=80=
=94 since climate change is an externality, private companies don=E2=80=99t=
 have sufficient incentive to invest in emissions-reducing technologies lik=
e tissue-culture meat. But there=E2=80=99s also the moral aspect of the iss=
ue =E2=80=94 only once acceptable substitutes become price-competitive will=
 humankind abandon the barbaric practice of animal farming.=20
In fact, there=E2=80=99s an important precedent for this: Forced labor. Eve=
n a cursory reading of history will show that forced human labor of one sor=
t or another was incredibly common throughout human history, in essentially=
 every society, and formed the basis of many social arrangements, values, t=
raditions, and cultures. But nowadays, though a bit of forced labor still e=
xists, it has become a relatively rare phenomenon. The reason, of course, i=
s mechanization. It=E2=80=99s cheaper to have machines do our farming and m=
ove our ships and carry our water than to force humans to do this work for =
us. And so we have allowed society to anathematize forced human labor. Once=
 we could maintain our consumption lifestyles without it, we allowed oursel=
ves to embrace a morality that forbade what we no longer needed.
Humans =E2=80=94 or at least, most humans =E2=80=94 are monstrous, but not =
infinitely so. I love meat, and I=E2=80=99m eager to switch to the tissue-c=
ultured variety. After tissue-culture meat becomes cheaper than animal-farm=
ed meat, there will be holdouts who insist that they won=E2=80=99t eat =E2=
=80=9Cfake=E2=80=9D meat, just as there are now people who refuse Covid vac=
cines and insist on blasting diesel smoke [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c=
/eJwlkEtuwyAURVcThoifExgw6CQL6AYQnxebBoMFuJF3X1xLiCtAT4d7vO0wl3rorbSOzs30Yw=
Od4dMS9A4V7Q2qiUEzSTjjAgUtApWTRLGZVwVYbUy61x3QtrsUve2x5HOAT1xMaNGSMecmJ4Vij=
gQVFEhCX8J57mSYOL-wdg8RsgcNv1CPkgElvfS-tRv_urHnWJDxJ77jBiFaXOo8rs7ziO-SUsyz=
8cUmFDUjjBLJyYgBxRQDMB8sKPAWJH2Nz4THIFPKCHgl-E2QdWa47a5169_YlxVV_VPaMl7OwLG=
d7QZgXfcc-2EgW5cgXMX7pe9fhZkhQx1ag7Fd0zsnTColFBX0KjrMCHIn4sEYGsRQxlTWudhli3=
mo-wNuAodw] into the air. But these people will be increasingly ostracized,=
 and over time their numbers will dwindle. Part of this will be economic, a=
s animal farming shrinks and loses its economies of scale, and the cost of =
eating animal meat goes up. But part will be a shift in our moral norms.=20
Morality is a coordination game =E2=80=94 once a critical number of people =
accept that animal farming is barbaric and wrong, fence-sitters will hop on=
 the bandwagon, and there will be a cascade effect where in just a short sp=
ace of time, animal farming will go from broadly accepted to anathematized.=
 In the resulting equilibrium, only iconoclasts and contrarians will insist=
 on eating meat cut from the bones of real animals. And eventually, anti-an=
imal-cruelty crusaders =E2=80=94 many of whom would have been perfectly com=
fortable making excuses for eating the products of factory farms just a few=
 decades ago, in a different social context =E2=80=94 will succeed in banni=
ng animal farming in most areas, and that will effectively be the end of it=
=2E=20
This future must be our goal. There is nothing dystopian or unnatural about=
 it =E2=80=94 it is just another step in the centuries-long process of a mo=
nstrous species using its intelligence and ingenuity to allow itself to be =
a little less monstrous. Since we=E2=80=99re too hideous to do the right th=
ing and give up animal farming today, we must do the next-best thing: Work =
to replace it with something cheaper and more delicious as soon as we possi=
bly can.

